Need to be sure to include a radiation feature, rx_summ_radiation

Field Description: This data item indicates the method of radiation therapy performed as part of the
first course of treatment.

0 : None; diagnosed at autopsy
1 : Beam radiation
2 : Radioactive implants
3 : Radioisotopes
4 : Combination of 1 with 2 or 3
5 : Radiation, NOS - method or source not specified
6 : other radiation (1973-1987 cases only)
7 : Patient or patient's guardian refused radiation therapy
8 : Radiation recommended, unknown if administered
9 : Unknown if radiation administered

http://seer.cancer.gov/data/seerstat/nov2014/TextData.FileDescription.pdf

http://www.benkuhn.net/survival-trees

Appendix: pseudocode for the reduction

def train(X, T, D)
    // X, T, D are the original dataset
    X' = []
    D' = []

    // the transformation
    for each index i in X:
        for t=1 to T[i]:
            new_D = (0 if t < T[i], else D[i])
            append new_D to D'
            new_X = (X[i], t)
            append new_X to X'

    return a decision tree trained on (X', D')

def pmf(h, X)
    // X is a single datapoint
    // returns an array A where A[i] = P(Y = i | X)
    A = []
    p_so_far = 1 // this is p(T >= t | X)
    for t = 1 to (the last month where h has any data):
        // h knows p(T = t | T >= t, X), we call this p_cur
        p_cur = h's prediction for (X, t)
        append (p_so_far * p_cur) to A
        p_so_far *= (1 - p_cur)

dft['survival_months'] = dft['survival_months'].copy().astype('int')
In [66]:
dftcopy = dft.reindex(np.repeat(dft.index.values, dft['survival_months'] + 1 ), method='ffill')


dftcopy['month'] += dftcopy.groupby(['patient_id_number']).cumcount()
In [67]:
dftcopy['newtarget'] = ((dftcopy['survival_months'] == dftcopy['month']) & (dftcopy['vital_status_recode_Dead'] == 1)).copy().astype('int')

from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity

So newindex runs from 0 to 46963 $\rightarrow$ we have 46964 patients. We want to break them up into two sets such that the proportions of 0s and 1s are the same in the two sets.

In [271]:
def measure_performance(X, y, clf, show_accuracy=True, show_classification_report=True, show_confusion_matrix=True):
    y_pred = clf.predict(X)
    if show_accuracy:
        print "Accuracy:{0:.3f}".format(metrics.accuracy_score(y, y_pred)), "\n"
    if show_classification_report:
        print "Classification report"
        print metrics.classification_report(y, y_pred), "\n"
    if show_confusion_matrix:
        print "Confusion matrix"
        print metrics.confusion_matrix(y, y_pred), "\n"

In [274]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, title='Confusion matrix', cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(target_names))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, target_names, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, target_names)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

# Plot feature importance
featureImportance = clf_dt.feature_importances_

# normalize by max importance
featureImportance = featureImportance / featureImportance.max()

#plot variable importance
idxSorted = numpy.argsort(featureImportance)[-15:]
barPos = numpy.arange(idxSorted.shape[0]) + .5
plot.barh(barPos, featureImportance[idxSorted], align='center')
plot.yticks(barPos, featurenames[idxSorted])
plot.xlabel('Variable Importance')
plot.show()

def get_survival_function(patient, df, clf):
    """Takes as input the value of newindex and returns
    an array corresponding to the cdf."""
    import operator
    import math
    dfcopy = df.loc[patient].copy()
    
    if type(dfcopy) != pd.core.series.Series:
        print df[['month','newtarget']].loc[patient].tail(1)
        print df[['month']].loc[patient].tail(1).values[0][0]
    else:
        print "Month: ", df[['month']].loc[patient].values[0]
    newtargetvalue = df[['newtarget']].loc[patient].tail(1).values[0]
    if newtargetvalue == 1:
        if type(dfcopy) != pd.core.series.Series:
            dfcopy_data = dfcopy[list(df.columns)[:-2]].iloc[0].values
        else:
            dfcopy_data = dfcopy.values[:-2]
        A = []
        p_so_far = 1
        for i in range(100):
            p_cur = clf.predict_proba(np.append(dfcopy_data, i))[0][1]
            A.append(p_so_far * p_cur)
            p_so_far = p_so_far*(1 - p_cur)
    
    
        index, value = max(enumerate(A), key=operator.itemgetter(1))
        As = pd.Series(A)
        
        if type(dfcopy) != pd.core.series.Series:
            absoluteerror = abs(index - df[['month']].loc[patient].tail(1).values[0][0])
        else:
            absoluteerror = abs(index - df[['month']].loc[patient]).values[0]
            
            
            
         
        print "Prediction: ", index, " with probability: ", value
        print "absolute error: ", absoluteerror
    
        As.plot()
        plt.title("PMF for Patient " + str(patient))
        
        Asurv = 1 - As.cumsum()
        
        Asurv.plot()
        plt.title("Survival Function for Patient " + str(patient))
    
        return Asurv
    
    else:
        print "not using that one", patient

        #print "Month: ", df[['month']].loc[patient].values[0]

        dfcopy_data = dfcopy.values[:-2]
    A = []
    p_so_far = 1
    for i in range(120):
        p_cur = clf.predict_proba(np.append(dfcopy_data, i))[0][1]
        A.append(p_so_far * p_cur)
        p_so_far = p_so_far*(1 - p_cur)
    
    
    index, value = max(enumerate(A), key=operator.itemgetter(1))

    #As.plot()

    Asurv = 1 - As.cumsum()
        
    #Asurv.plot()
    #plt.title("Survival Function for Patient " + str(patient))
    
    return Asurv, dfcopy_data
In [329]:
def plot_survival_function_all(patient, df, clf):
    """Takes as input the value of newindex and returns
    an array corresponding to the cdf."""
    import operator
    import math
    dfcopy = df.loc[patient].copy()
    
    if type(dfcopy) != pd.core.series.Series:
        print df[['month','newtarget']].loc[patient].tail(1)
        print df[['month']].loc[patient].tail(1).values[0][0]
    else:
        print "Month: ", df[['month']].loc[patient].values[0]
    newtargetvalue = df[['newtarget']].loc[patient].tail(1).values[0]
    
    if type(dfcopy) != pd.core.series.Series:
        dfcopy_data = dfcopy[list(df.columns)[:-2]].iloc[0].values
    else:
        dfcopy_data = dfcopy.values[:-2]
    A = []
    p_so_far = 1
    for i in range(120):
        p_cur = clf.predict_proba(np.append(dfcopy_data, i))[0][1]
        A.append(p_so_far * p_cur)
        p_so_far = p_so_far*(1 - p_cur)
    
    
    index, value = max(enumerate(A), key=operator.itemgetter(1))
    As = pd.Series(A)
        
    if type(dfcopy) != pd.core.series.Series:
        absoluteerror = abs(index - df[['month']].loc[patient].tail(1).values[0][0])
    else:
        absoluteerror = abs(index - df[['month']].loc[patient]).values[0]
            
            
            
         
    print "Prediction: ", index, " with probability: ", value
    print "absolute error: ", absoluteerror
    
    Asurv = 1 - As.cumsum()
    
    print "Probablity of surviving to 6 months: ", Asurv.loc[6]
    
    print "Probability of surviving to 12 months: ", Asurv.loc[12]
    
    print "Probability of surviving to 60 months: ", Asurv.loc[60]
    
    As.plot()
    plt.title("PMF for Patient " + str(patient))
        

        
    Asurv.plot()
    #plt.title("Survival Function for Patient " + str(patient))
    
    return Asurv

prob6pos = (result6['prob_to_6_months'] >= .5)
prob6neg = (result6['prob_to_6_months'] < .5)
surv6pos = (result6['survival_months'] >= 6)
surv6neg = (result6['survival_months'] < 6)


tp = result6[prob6pos & surv6pos].shape[0]
fp = result6[prob6pos & surv6neg].shape[0]
tn = result6[prob6neg & surv6neg].shape[0]
fn = result6[prob6neg & surv6pos].shape[0]

In [352]:
def get_rates_60():
    """need to loop through threshold values 
    high to low, accumulate the true positive rates and
    false positive rates into a list and then turn it
    all into three arrays and return them."""

    fprlist = []
    tprlist = []
    
    ctClass = [-0.01 + i*0.01 for i in range(103)][::-1]
    
    duh = list(np.arange(1.1,-.01, -.01))
    
    duh = ctClass
    
    for i in range(len(duh)):
        print duh[i], type(float(duh[i]))
        prob60pos = (result60['prob_to_60_months'] >= float(duh[i]))   # this value here is the threshold
        prob60neg = (result60['prob_to_60_months'] < float(duh[i]))
        surv60pos = (result60['survival_months'] >= 60)
        surv60neg = (result60['survival_months'] < 60)


        tp = result60[prob60pos & surv60pos].shape[0]
        fp = result60[prob60pos & surv60neg].shape[0]
        tn = result60[prob60neg & surv60neg].shape[0]
        fn = result60[prob60neg & surv60pos].shape[0]

        accuracy = (tp + tn) / float(tp + fp + tn + fn)


        print "Predictions for suriving at least 60 months: "

        print "accuracy: ", accuracy


        tpr = tp/float(tp + fn)

        print "True Positive rate: ", tpr
        
        tprlist.append(tpr)

        fpr = fp/float(fp + tn)

        print "False positive rate: ", fpr

        fprlist.append(fpr)

        print "Confusion matrix:"
        print tp, fn
        print fp, tn
        
    return tprlist, fprlist

In [356]:
def get_rates_6():
    """need to loop through threshold values 
    high to low, accumulate the true positive rates and
    false positive rates into a list and then turn it
    all into three arrays and return them."""

    fprlist = []
    tprlist = []
    
    ctClass = [-0.01 + i*0.01 for i in range(103)][::-1]
    
    duh = list(np.arange(1.1,-.01, -.01))
    
    duh = ctClass
    
    for i in range(len(duh)):
        print duh[i], type(float(duh[i]))
        prob6pos = (result6['prob_to_6_months'] >= float(duh[i]))   # this value here is the threshold
        prob6neg = (result6['prob_to_6_months'] < float(duh[i]))
        surv6pos = (result6['survival_months'] >= 6)
        surv6neg = (result6['survival_months'] < 6)


        tp = result6[prob6pos & surv6pos].shape[0]
        fp = result6[prob6pos & surv6neg].shape[0]
        tn = result6[prob6neg & surv6neg].shape[0]
        fn = result6[prob6neg & surv6pos].shape[0]

        accuracy = (tp + tn) / float(tp + fp + tn + fn)


        print "Predictions for suriving at least 6 months: "

        print "accuracy: ", accuracy


        tpr = tp/float(tp + fn)

        print "True Positive rate: ", tpr
        
        tprlist.append(tpr)

        fpr = fp/float(fp + tn)

        print "False positive rate: ", fpr

        fprlist.append(fpr)

        print "Confusion matrix:"
        print tp, fn
        print fp, tn
        
    return tprlist, fprlist

In [360]:
def get_rates_12():
    """need to loop through threshold values 
    high to low, accumulate the true positive rates and
    false positive rates into a list and then turn it
    all into three arrays and return them."""

    fprlist = []
    tprlist = []
    
    ctClass = [-0.01 + i*0.01 for i in range(103)][::-1]
    
    duh = list(np.arange(1.1,-.01, -.01))
    
    duh = ctClass
    
    for i in range(len(duh)):
        print duh[i], type(float(duh[i]))
        prob12pos = (result12['prob_to_12_months'] >= float(duh[i]))   # this value here is the threshold
        prob12neg = (result12['prob_to_12_months'] < float(duh[i]))
        surv12pos = (result12['survival_months'] >= 12)
        surv12neg = (result12['survival_months'] < 12)


        tp = result12[prob12pos & surv12pos].shape[0]
        fp = result12[prob12pos & surv12neg].shape[0]
        tn = result12[prob12neg & surv12neg].shape[0]
        fn = result12[prob12neg & surv12pos].shape[0]

        accuracy = (tp + tn) / float(tp + fp + tn + fn)


        print "Predictions for suriving at least 12 months: "

        print "accuracy: ", accuracy


        tpr = tp/float(tp + fn)

        print "True Positive rate: ", tpr
        
        tprlist.append(tpr)

        fpr = fp/float(fp + tn)

        print "False positive rate: ", fpr

        fprlist.append(fpr)

        print "Confusion matrix:"
        print tp, fn
        print fp, tn
        
    return tprlist, fprlist

In [362]:
fpr12 = np.array(fpr12list)
tpr12 = np.array(tpr12list)
In [363]:
ctClass = [i*0.01 for i in range(101)]

areaUnderCurve = np.trapz(y=tpr12, x = fpr12)

plot.plot(fpr12, tpr12, linewidth=2)
plot.plot(ctClass, ctClass, linestyle=':')
plot.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plot.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plot.title('ROC Curve for Predicting \n 12 month survival \n AUC: ' + str(areaUnderCurve) + '\n Prostate Cancer')
plot.show()

Need to save the objects¶

  • dft
  • dftcopytrain
  • dftcopytest
  • rf
  • dfprobs This is the one that takes the most time to create

According to the article http://gim.unmc.edu/dxtests/roc3.htm AUC values can be interpreted as follows:

  • .9 - 1 = excellent(A)
  • .8 - .9 = good(B)
  • .7 = .8 = fair(C)
  • .6 - .7 = poor(D)
  • .5 - .6 = fail(F)
In [364]:
from pandas.io.pytables import HDFStore
In [365]:
store = HDFStore("mymalegendata.h5")
In [366]:
store['dftmalegen'] = dft
In [367]:
store['dftmalegencopytrain'] = dftcopytrain
In [368]:
store['dftmalegencopytest'] = dftcopytest
In [369]:
store['dfmalegenprobs'] = dfprobs

To load these dataframes back:

from pandas.io.pytables import HDFStore

newstore = HDFStore("mymalegendata.h5")

dftcopytrain = newstore['dftmalegencopytrain']
In [370]:
store.close()
In [ ]:
